  "introduction": "**The Mystery Box Hook**: Teacher holds up a box containing a single grain of rice (or shows an image). Ask: 'If I give you this, is it alive? No. But if I tell you that every living thing on Earth—from the smallest ant to the largest blue whale—is made of billions of these tiny units... what are they?' Reveal images of cork cells under a microscope and ask students to guess why Hooke called them 'cells'."
  "theory": {
    "overview": "Cells are the fundamental building blocks of life. The study began with Robert Hooke's observation of dead plant tissue, leading to the classification of all living things into two main types: Prokaryotes (simple) and Eukaryotes (complex).",
    "keyPoints": [
      "Robert Hooke discovered cells in 1665 using a microscope on cork.",
      "Prokaryotic cells lack a true nucleus; their DNA is free-floating.",
      "Eukaryotic cells have a defined nucleus and membrane-bound organelles."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "The concept of the cell revolutionized biology. Before Hooke, people did not know that life was composed of discrete units. When he looked at cork under his microscope, he saw empty compartments which he named 'cells'. It is crucial to note these were dead cells (cell walls only). Later scientists discovered living protoplasm. The distinction between Prokaryotic and Eukaryotic cells is the most fundamental classification in biology. Prokaryotes (like bacteria) are simpler and lack a nuclear membrane, while Eukaryotes (plants, animals, fungi) have complex internal structures including a nucleus that houses genetic material."
  },
